# Changelog OG Image / Featured Image Rework — Implementation Plan

## Overview

Decouple OG image generation from in-page hero images, restructure the changelog layout to remove the shared "Changelog" heading from individual entry pages, and standardise programmatic OG images across all content types (blog, changelog, legal, docs).

Currently, the `ogImage` frontmatter field serves two unrelated purposes: social sharing metadata (`<meta og:image>`) and in-page hero image rendering. Since programmatic `opengraph-image.tsx` route handlers already override the meta tags for blog and changelog, the frontmatter URL is redundant for social sharing. A new `featuredImage` field on `ContentPageSchema` will handle in-page hero images as a separate concern.

## Current State Analysis

### ogImage Field
- **Schema**: `ogImage: z.url()` on `BasePageSchema` (`content-schemas.ts:21`) — required, inherited by all 4 content types
- **Meta tags**: `seo-bundle.ts:70,80` feeds `ogImage` into `openGraph.images` and `twitter.images` — but these are overridden by colocated `opengraph-image.tsx` route handlers for blog and changelog
- **In-page hero**: `changelog/[slug]/page.tsx:90-101` and `blog/[slug]/page.tsx:135-145` render `ogImage` as an `<Image>` hero — changelog guards against `og-default.png`, blog does not
- **JSON-LD**: `builders/blog.ts:38` and `builders/changelog.ts:37` use `ogImage` as the Article `image` URL
- **All 17 MDX files** have `ogImage` in frontmatter — blog/changelog/legal use `og-default.png`, docs/api use custom paths like `https://lightfast.ai/og/docs/...`

### Changelog Layout
- `changelog/layout.tsx:11-24` renders "Changelog" `<h1>` + RSS link, wrapping both listing and entry pages
- Blog uses the inverse pattern: `blog/layout.tsx` is a bare pass-through; `blog/(listing)/layout.tsx` owns the heading + RSS

### OG Route Handlers
- Blog: `blog/[slug]/opengraph-image.tsx` — uses `ContentLayout`
- Changelog: `changelog/[slug]/opengraph-image.tsx` — uses `ContentLayout`
- Legal: **none** — falls back to frontmatter `ogImage` URL
- Docs: **none** — falls back to frontmatter `ogImage` URL
- API Reference: **none** — OpenAPI virtual pages use `createMetadata` directly

### Key Discoveries:
- `ContentSeoData` (`content-schemas.ts:91-104`) picks `ogImage` from `BlogPostData` — used as the input type for `buildArticleMetadata`
- `emitLegalSeo` (`seo-bundle.ts:166,175`) references `data.ogImage` directly (not through `buildArticleMetadata`)
- `builders/docs.ts`, `builders/legal.ts`, `builders/api-reference.ts` do NOT use `ogImage` — only blog and changelog builders do
- Blog listing page (`blog/(listing)/`) does NOT use `ogImage` — only the entry page does
- Changelog listing page (`changelog/page.tsx:135-146`) uses `ogImage` for preview cards
- `@repo/og` has 4 layouts: `ContentLayout`, `HomeLayout`, `DocsLayout`, `FeatureLayout` — only `ContentLayout` is currently used

## Desired End State

After this plan is complete:
1. `ogImage` is removed from all schemas, types, SEO functions, builders, and MDX frontmatter
2. `featuredImage` (optional string) exists on `ContentPageSchema` for in-page hero images in blog and changelog
3. All content types have programmatic `opengraph-image.tsx` route handlers using `@repo/og` layouts
4. Changelog entry pages no longer show the "Changelog" heading + RSS link (listing page only)
5. Changelog entry pages own their own centering (`max-w-2xl pt-24 pb-32`)

### How to verify:
- `pnpm typecheck` passes with no `ogImage` references remaining
- All content pages render correct programmatic OG images (verify via browser devtools `<meta og:image>`)
- Changelog listing page shows heading + RSS; entry pages do not
- Blog/changelog entries render `featuredImage` as hero when set, no hero when absent

## What We're NOT Doing

- Removing `ogTitle` or `ogDescription` from schemas — these are still useful for meta tag customisation
- Adding `featuredImage` to `LegalPageSchema` or `DocsPageSchema` — legal/docs pages don't need hero images
- Changing the `@repo/og` layout components themselves
- Modifying the MDX `img` component or `NextImage` component
- Restructuring the blog layout (it already follows the correct pattern)

## Implementation Approach

Work bottom-up: schema → SEO layer → OG handlers → layout → page components → frontmatter. This ordering ensures TypeScript catches all broken references as we remove `ogImage`, and each phase builds on the previous one.

---

## Phase 1: Schema & Type Changes

### Overview
Remove `ogImage` from the base schema, add `featuredImage` to content pages, update the SEO data type.

### Changes Required:

#### 1. Content Schemas

**File**: `apps/www/src/lib/content-schemas.ts`

**Remove `ogImage` from `BasePageSchema`** (line 21):

```typescript
const BasePageSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1),
  description: z.string().min(50).max(160),
  keywords: z.array(z.string().min(1)).min(3).max(20),
  canonicalUrl: z.url(),
  ogTitle: z.string().min(1).max(70),
  ogDescription: z.string().min(50).max(160),
  // ogImage removed — programmatic opengraph-image.tsx handles OG images
  noindex: z.boolean().default(false),
  nofollow: z.boolean().default(false),
});
```

**Add `featuredImage` to `ContentPageSchema`** (after line 30):

```typescript
const ContentPageSchema = BasePageSchema.extend({
  authors: z.array(AuthorSchema).min(1),
  publishedAt: z.iso.datetime(),
  updatedAt: z.iso.datetime(),
  faq: z.array(FaqItemSchema).min(1),
  featuredImage: z.string().optional(),
});
```

**Remove `ogImage` from `ContentSeoData`** (lines 91-104):

```typescript
export type ContentSeoData = Pick<
  BlogPostData,
  | "authors"
  | "description"
  | "keywords"
  | "nofollow"
  | "noindex"
  | "ogDescription"
  | "ogTitle"
  | "publishedAt"
  | "title"
  | "updatedAt"
>;
```

### Success Criteria:

#### Automated Verification:
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` reports errors ONLY in files that still reference `ogImage` (seo-bundle, builders, page components) — these are fixed in subsequent phases

